tweet: @srchvrs @thegautamkamath Of course not, as is the case with all generalizations. I‚Äôm speaking about the community consensus from what I‚Äôve gathered over the years. If the question was, ‚Äúhow can author ordering be improved to be more fair‚Äù, I‚Äôd agree with other comments on alphabetical or randomized.

name: Mariya I. Vasileva
tweet: As reviewers, we also have a part to play in making sure this doesn‚Äôt happen.

name: Mariya I. Vasileva
tweet: @thegautamkamath Authors beyond the second are ordered on relevance and contribution to the project, which is a decision typically made by the first author, and may be miscalculated. Often, equal contribution causes conflicts in ordering. Also, middle authors can be added for ‚Äúpolitical‚Äù reasons.

name: Mariya I. Vasileva
tweet: @thegautamkamath The last author is typically the first author‚Äôs advisor, or if they differ, the advisor who wrote the grant funding the project. Author ordering is of course imperfect and there seem to be many subjective decisions to make.

name: Mariya I. Vasileva
tweet: @thegautamkamath In machine learning and computer vision, it‚Äôs implied that a first author has generally done 70-90% of the technical work in the paper. A second and plus author is understood to have contributed bits and pieces like testing a particular baseline, or visualizing a set of results.

name: Mariya I. Vasileva
tweet: I weekly come across a new paper in machine learning and computer vision that attempts to score a model for a human cognitive process in a completely arbitrary manner, without consulting any cognitive science or psychophysics literature. Why?
